Anda bisa jadi mengandalkan useMemo sebagai salah satu optimasi performa, bukan sebagai jaminan semantic. Di masa yang akan datang, React bisa saja memilih untuk "forget" beberapa nilai-nilai hasil memoize sebelumnya dan menghitung ulang pada render selanjutnya, contohnya untuk mengosongkan memori dari komponen-komponen offscreen. Tulis kode Anda agar kode tersebut dapat terus berjalan tanpa useMemo ‚Äî dan menambahkannya ke performa yang teroptimasi. (Untuk kasus yang langka ketika sebuah nilai harus tidak pernah dikomputasi ulang, Anda bisa menginisiasi secara lazy (initialize lazily) sebuah ref.)

Newer GPL versions are not GPL3 compatible. Transitioning from GPL2 to GPL3 was a pain for many projects because they do not include the "or later" clause.
The FSF recommends to include the "or later" clause to allow relicensing with newer versions. When GPLv4 comes out, either us or any third party is allowed to reuse the project in GPLv4. This is not the default.

Based on #1876 (comment), here are the changes applied:

Killed contribute for contribution flow routes that don't have a tier

Impact: If collectives have linked to these routes, they'll now end up on the tiers page instead
Example: /babel/contribute => Babel Tiers page


Moved all tier routes for contribution flow

From_/:collective/:verb/tier/:tierId-:tierSlug
To___/:collective/contribute/:tierSlug-:tierId/checkout
Example: /babel/donate/tier/42-blabla => /babel/contribute/blabla-42/checkout
Impact: Older routes will still work but they're marked as deprecated in the code




Which gives the following routing table:

/babel/contribute => tiers page
/babel/contribute/blabla-42 => tier page for tier 42
/babel/contribute/blabla-42/checkout => contribution flow for tier 42
/babel/donate => contribution flow to donate without a tier


If we're good with this (I am) then I'll follow up in another issue for us to watch the logs and kill the unused routes after some time.

regarding the StackNavigator and history--basically I see it like this: if you deep-link, u probably should wipe previous history state, but if not, just always remember exactly where the user was. I much prefer that experience over starting over again like most apps do.
Regarding the overkill stuff, the  history state plus memory memoryHistory is basically an object with an array. So the only overkill is the views like StackNavigator itself, which you need anyway.
Otherwise I think in the React Navigation docs I discuss how to do back handling--basically drown the routes of each of your Stack Routers (i.e. stack navigators). That's the most fool proof way to do it. There is some manual work--and it's a good thing--it allows u to configure logic on what routes should be drained first and in what order.
...actually it looks like i dont discuss it. But basically in the handler u use for your BackHandler, dispatch a React Navigation action with the nav key of the corresponding StackRouter you want to drain, and intertwine such actions with actions to close drawers, and shift tabs. Shifting tabs will likely happen from backing out of the stack router attached to it. I gotta pattern for this that is super nice. I wish I documented it. crap.

What and why still apply. What did you do to solve an issue and how? Why it was solved in a certain way and not in a different way?
